    train = pickle.load(training_data)

    test = pickle.load(testing_data)

with open('./traffic_data/valid.p', mode = 'rb') as validating_data:
    valid = pickle.load(validating_data)

# Convert images to Greyscale Images and Perform Normalization
from sklearn.utils import shuffle

X_train, y_train = shuffle(X_train, y_train)


X_train_grey = np.sum(X_train/3, axis=3, keepdims=True)
X_test_grey =  np.sum(X_test/3, axis = 3, keepdims= True)
X_valid_grey = np.sum(X_valid/3, axis = 3, keepdims= True)

Build a Deep Concolution Neural Networks¶

In [ ]:
from tensorflow.keras import  layers, models

CNN = models.Sequential()

CNN.add(layers.Conv2D(6, (5,5), activation = 'relu', input_shape = (32,32, 1)))
CNN.add(layers.AveragePooling2D())

CNN.add(layers.Dropout(0.2))# Dropout Layer

CNN.add(layers.Conv2D(16, (5,5), activation = 'relu'))
CNN.add(layers.AveragePooling2D())

CNN.add(layers.Flatten())# Flattening Layer

CNN.add(layers.Dense(120, activation = 'relu'))
CNN.add(layers.Dense(84, activation = 'relu'))
CNN.add(layers.Dense(43, activation = 'softmax'))
CNN.summary()

        y_train,
        batch_size = 500,
        verbose = 1,
        epochs = 30,
        validation_data = (X_valid_norm, y_valid))

# Plotting the results
plt.figure(figsize=(12,12))
start_index = 0

for i in range(25):
    plt.subplot(5, 5 ,i+1)
    plt.grid = False
    plt.xticks([])
    plt.yticks([])

    pred = np.argmax(predicted[start_index+i])
    gt = y_test[start_index+i]

    col = 'g'
    if pred != gt:
        col = 'r'

    plt.xlabel('i={} , pred={}, gt={}'.format(start_index+i, pred, gt), color = col)
    plt.imshow(X_test[start_index+i], cmap='binary')
